WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.050 --> 00:00:03.310
&gt;&gt; Marisa Bellack:
Hi there everyone.

00:00:03.310 --> 00:00:06.110
Look comfy on those
bean bag chairs.

00:00:08.190 --> 00:00:11.140
Hello, I'm Marisa
Bellack, I'm an editor

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:12.880
at the Washington Post,

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:15.290
a charter sponsor of
the book festival.

00:00:15.290 --> 00:00:18.050
And I'm pleased to
introduce Meg Medina.

00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:21.300
Author of books for children,
pre-teens and young adults

00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:24.400
that feature strong
Latina characters grappling

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:28.270
with questions of culture
and identity and facing some

00:00:28.270 --> 00:00:31.320
of the central challenges
of our time.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:35.820
Meg touches on family separation
in her book Tia Isa Wants a Car

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:40.150
which received the 2012 Ezra
Jack Keats New Writer Award.

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:43.080
She deals with migration in
her young adult novel The Girl

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:44.960
Who Could Silence the Wind.

00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:46.390
She writes about bullying

00:00:46.390 --> 00:00:48.950
in Yaqui Delgado Wants
to Kick Your Ass.

00:00:48.950 --> 00:00:51.140
Which was banned from
some school libraries and

00:00:51.140 --> 00:00:54.500
yet won the American Library
Associations top honor

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:57.160
for Latino Children
and Young Authors.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:01.680
Although she was named
Margret Rose after the sister

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:05.510
of Queen Elizabeth, Meg is the
daughter of Cuban immigrants.

00:01:05.510 --> 00:01:08.700
She was born in Virginia
and raised in Queens.

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:11.910
She's a founding member
of We Need Diverse Books.

00:01:11.910 --> 00:01:15.280
And regularly notes the
depressing statistics that less

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:19.860
than 3% of children's books
are by or about Latinos.

00:01:19.860 --> 00:01:23.140
I imagine she may speak
about that some here today.

00:01:23.140 --> 00:01:26.310
Her newest book is Merci
Suarez Changes Gears.

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:28.780
It's a story she says
about how to say goodbye

00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:31.180
to the important things in life.

00:01:31.180 --> 00:01:33.440
The book actually isn't
out until September 11th

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:36.250
but I understand there are
copies available at the festival

00:01:36.250 --> 00:01:38.660
and Meg is scheduled
for a signing session

00:01:38.660 --> 00:01:41.410
from five to six this evening.

00:01:41.410 --> 00:01:43.840
Before we dive into our
discussion I'm suppose

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:45.140
to mention that the Library

00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:46.590
of Congress has been
the festivals host

00:01:46.590 --> 00:01:48.740
since the festival
began 18 years ago.

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:52.470
I want to thank festival
co-chairman David Rubenstein

00:01:52.470 --> 00:01:55.530
and the many sponsors who
made this event possible.

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:57.390
You can support the
festival with a donation,

00:01:57.390 --> 00:01:59.400
there's information
in your program.

00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:01.720
Please note too that there
will be time for questions

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:03.550
after Meg's remarks and anyone

00:02:03.550 --> 00:02:05.180
who asks a question
will be filmed

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:06.880
for the library's archives.

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:10.510
Now please help me
welcome Meg Medina.

00:02:10.510 --> 00:02:16.350
[ Applause ]

00:02:16.350 --> 00:02:18.380
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: Thank
you so much.

00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:21.990
Buenas tardes, good afternoon
everybody, thanks for coming

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:24.130
out tonight and this afternoon

00:02:24.130 --> 00:02:26.780
and you're right you can't
see anybody from up here.

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:28.800
So you're all invisible except

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:32.260
for these really comfortable
kids on the bean bag chairs

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:36.480
and next year can you please
ask them to put a bean bag chair

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:40.110
up here for me because that
would be kind of fun to be able

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:41.670
to talk with you from there.

00:02:41.670 --> 00:02:45.600
So I am here, this
is me and my Bitmoji.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.100
I discovered bitmojis
like a year ago

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:52.180
and now I'm unstoppable, I
have a bitmoji for everything.

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:55.180
And this is Meg bitmoji who's
going to be our concierge today.

00:02:55.180 --> 00:03:00.010
And I'm here to talk about
Merci Suarez Changes Gears

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:04.990
and you notice that it's a girl
on a bike and we do change gears

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:07.600
on a bike and it
becomes harder to pedal.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.520
But we change gears over
the course of our life

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:13.260
and that's sort of
the idea of that book.

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:17.020
That book did not start as a
novel, it started like this.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:21.950
I was asked to write a
story for an anthology,

00:03:21.950 --> 00:03:25.160
which is a collection of
stories called Flying Lessons

00:03:25.160 --> 00:03:26.600
and Other Stories.

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:28.810
And it had some really
great authors,

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.250
some of my favorites were
in there like Jackie Woodson

00:03:31.250 --> 00:03:37.060
and Kwamer Alexander and Matt
de la Pena and others and so

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:39.430
when they asked me to
write a story they said,

00:03:39.430 --> 00:03:42.110
Meg we want a story
the only thing you have

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:46.140
to do is make sure that the
character is Latina like you.

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:49.840
You can tell us any story
that you want to tell us.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.450
And I said I can?

00:03:51.450 --> 00:03:56.830
And all of us did, here's
some of us at ALA one year.

00:03:56.830 --> 00:04:00.820
So I was thinking about it and
I thought back, I had a memory

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:05.270
of a time when I was
playing with my best friend.

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:07.580
When I was in elementary
school and my best friend

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:11.580
in elementary school
I think you know her.

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:14.240
Her name is Raquel,
but you know her

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:18.220
as RJ Palacio who wrote Wonder.

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:21.770
And so we lived like a block
and a half away from each other

00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:25.740
and Raquel is from Colombia
and my family was from Cuba.

00:04:25.740 --> 00:04:28.300
And so our mothers could
talk to each other in Espanol

00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:33.260
and we were good friends and
one day Raquel and I were

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:38.100
in the back of her house
and the ambulance came.

00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:42.840
And the police came and all
these adults were standing

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:44.640
around and not letting us look

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.530
and we were like,
what happened right?

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:52.750
And so sadly what had happened
is that there was a gentleman

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:56.360
who lived in her building by
himself, an older gentleman

00:04:56.360 --> 00:05:01.270
and he had passed away, he
had died and no one knew.

00:05:01.270 --> 00:05:06.260
And so we as little kids were
like oh my gosh we've been

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:08.730
in this building with
a dead body for days

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:11.810
and we were all freaked
out about this.

00:05:11.810 --> 00:05:18.920
But over time, over the years
I've thought about that man

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:24.290
and his living alone and
the way that he passed away

00:05:24.290 --> 00:05:27.660
and it was just a story that
just always stuck with me.

00:05:27.660 --> 00:05:32.140
So when I was writing
Soul Painting, the story,

00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:35.870
I started with a dead body.

00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:38.580
That's found in the
condominium in Florida

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:41.120
where Merci Suarez lives.

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:46.810
And that morning her father, who
owns Soul Painting Inc arrives

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:49.370
to pick her up, her
and her brother Roli.

00:05:49.370 --> 00:05:54.980
And they're going to spend
the day painting the gym

00:05:54.980 --> 00:06:00.480
at their new school in
exchange for tuition reduction.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.720
And of course her father
notices this is apartment

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:06.130
with a person who died etcetera.

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:08.250
And the story's really
about what it's

00:06:08.250 --> 00:06:13.590
like to be the scholarship kid
in a school where everybody sort

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:16.390
of has more money than you.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:19.750
And it's a story about what that
looks like, what that feels like

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:22.680
and what it's like for a kid

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:27.970
to see their family
making sacrifices for them.

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:31.840
Okay it was a great
story, I loved it,

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:35.530
the book did really well, I
even did the recording of it

00:06:35.530 --> 00:06:39.040
in my own voice which was
really fun and a little scary.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.950
But when I was finished I
thought I was not really

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:46.980
finished because here's
what happens to writers.

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:51.290
The character gets in your
brain, it's like a worm.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:54.610
And then I'd be walking
around going,

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:58.710
I wonder who else Merci
lived with in Florida.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:04.480
I wonder how it really went for
her at Seaward Pines Academy.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.700
I wonder who the pain in
the neck is in her class.

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:11.930
I wonder does she have
primos and tias and tios,

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:15.210
like what's the whole shebang.

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:20.490
And so my editor Kate who's
this woman in the picture,

00:07:20.490 --> 00:07:22.780
we were together one day
and I was explaining to her

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:25.620
that I couldn't get Merci
and Roli and Poppi and Momi

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.110
out of my head and
she said that's

00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:31.610
because you're not
finished with the story.

00:07:31.610 --> 00:07:34.050
You have to keep writing.

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:37.400
So I did and I decided
okay I'm going

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:40.230
to turn this story into a novel.

00:07:40.230 --> 00:07:45.570
And that's the story that is
now Merci Suarez Changes Gears.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:50.000
Here's the thing, that's what
it looked like as a story

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.870
and this is the cover now.

00:07:51.870 --> 00:07:57.240
But here's the thing, turning
a story into a novel is

00:07:57.240 --> 00:08:02.000
like turning a fish
into a mango.

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:10.450
So the fish and the mango are
both colorful, they're the same.

00:08:10.450 --> 00:08:12.980
The fish and the mango
you could say are kind

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:15.180
of tropical, that's the same.

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:19.910
If you want to be really scary
you could say you could eat both

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:24.770
of those things, yes that's true
but they're nothing the same.

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:28.180
And that's the thing
about writing a novel.

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:32.150
That a story is just like a tiny
little piece of someone's life

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:35.320
but a novel is the whole thing.

00:08:35.320 --> 00:08:39.190
So I had to rethink
this whole story.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:41.800
And I decided that I was
going to think about family

00:08:41.800 --> 00:08:43.900
because that's what I
normally write about.

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:48.400
So I don't know what your
family is like, but I'm going

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:49.830
to tell you about my familia.

00:08:49.830 --> 00:08:54.960
When I think family,
it was not me

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:58.450
and mommy and my sister Lydia.

00:08:58.450 --> 00:09:02.370
When I say family I
mean it in a big way.

00:09:02.370 --> 00:09:05.180
With my aunts and my
uncles and my grandmother,

00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:08.150
I'm the kid in the yellow dress.

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:12.910
And the ladies is my aunt,
my mother, my grandmother

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:15.820
and my other aunt, [foreign
word] and [foreign word].

00:09:15.820 --> 00:09:19.060
And over here looking
very miserable on the day

00:09:19.060 --> 00:09:26.190
of my holy communion is
me with [foreign word]

00:09:26.190 --> 00:09:30.240
and [foreign word], [foreign
word] is this one on this side.

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:33.090
She was very interesting she
use to watch lucha libre,

00:09:33.090 --> 00:09:37.590
which is mass Mexican
wrestling on TV.

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:41.260
And she would always be
my after school babysitter

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:44.710
and tell me crazy
kinds of scary stories

00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:48.950
like when the hurricane wiped
out her village etcetera.

00:09:48.950 --> 00:09:52.520
And [foreign word]
was my fathers mother

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:56.850
and she was the scary abuela,
do you have scary abuelas,

00:09:56.850 --> 00:10:00.040
grandma sometimes, very strict?

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:04.080
Who makes you eat radishes
and your salad and they insist

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:07.380
that you wash your hands and you
have to be a little more formal

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:09.990
than you normally are, that
was abuela [foreign word]

00:10:09.990 --> 00:10:15.010
and she was also a seamstress,

00:10:15.010 --> 00:10:17.450
that's a person who
sews clothes.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:20.330
She worked in Manhattan
and every year

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:23.280
on my birthday abuela
[foreign word] would show

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:30.140
up with bags filled with my
entire wardrobe for the year.

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:32.030
Which was great because
my mother worked

00:10:32.030 --> 00:10:35.410
in a factory she could not
afford to buy me clothes

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:37.520
and [foreign word] made them all

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:40.220
without asking me once
what color I liked,

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:43.420
whether I wanted shorts,
a dress, nada right?

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:46.900
They came and you see this
picture of me in the bed,

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.830
I have 12 of them, one
for every year of my life,

00:10:49.830 --> 00:10:52.950
right I'm sitting, it
was a staged photograph

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:56.840
and I was suppose to look
very grateful for the clothes,

00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:59.030
I hope I look grateful there.

00:10:59.030 --> 00:11:03.990
So I was thinking about my
abuelas, like family right?

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:07.090
And then I was thinking
about how this would look

00:11:07.090 --> 00:11:09.300
in Merci's life and
then I thought

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:15.090
about how my mother always
wanted us to live all together.

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:17.110
It was her dream.

00:11:17.110 --> 00:11:21.140
She had a cousin in Miami who
lived in three houses just

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:23.630
like this, these flat top houses

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:26.820
that the family had
connected one to the other

00:11:26.820 --> 00:11:32.460
with little hallways and covered
roof ways, Julia lived in one,

00:11:32.460 --> 00:11:36.910
Julie lived in the second
one and then Julieta,

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:39.200
the youngest one
lived in the third.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:43.520
So three generations of a
family all in one compound.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:47.910
I thought [foreign word],
right who would want to live

00:11:47.910 --> 00:11:51.980
with relatives because they
all tell you what you do.

00:11:51.980 --> 00:11:56.240
When to wash your hands,
what show you can watch,

00:11:56.240 --> 00:12:00.420
you have to babysit a little
cousin, you know how it is.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:01.840
So I thought this was crazy

00:12:01.840 --> 00:12:05.570
but my mother thought
this was heaven.

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:09.180
So when I was writing Merci
Suarez Changes Gears I said you

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:11.920
know what she's going to live in
Florida and she's going to live

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:16.780
in three houses with
a big Badinski family.

00:12:16.780 --> 00:12:20.410
And so I gave her abuela and
abuelo, the grandparents,

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:23.990
I gave her tia Inez with these
two psycho five year old twins

00:12:23.990 --> 00:12:26.820
that are always getting
in trouble.

00:12:26.820 --> 00:12:31.650
But then I said okay I also
need to give her a school life.

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:34.680
And someone at school
who really annoys her,

00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:39.010
so I gave her Edna Santos.

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:46.530
Edna Santos who always says no
offense but, like no offense

00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:49.370
but you don't spell well.

00:12:49.370 --> 00:12:51.990
No offense but I
don't like your shirt.

00:12:51.990 --> 00:12:57.460
No offense but your
eyeglasses are funny etcetera.

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.980
We all know an Edna Santos.

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:02.500
So I gave her Edna Santos.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:05.930
But I had to give
her a bigger problem

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:08.080
and when I'm writing
books for kids I

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:11.130
like to tell them the truth
so I was thinking about some

00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:15.490
of the problems that my
own family faced now.

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:17.430
And here was some of them.

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:20.290
The first I was remembering
abuelas sewing room

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.900
and that thing that use to scare
me when I slept over at night

00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:26.030
because it has no head and legs.

00:13:26.030 --> 00:13:29.780
And at night it cast big
shadows like a ghost.

00:13:29.780 --> 00:13:33.070
But then I was thinking
of current life

00:13:33.070 --> 00:13:37.140
and here's my husbands mother,
my kids call her Ola who was

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:40.360
in her 90's and had
come to live with us.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:44.550
At the same time that my
mother who was very sick

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:48.830
and in her 80's had come
to live with us too.

00:13:48.830 --> 00:13:53.260
At the same time that
tia Esa who was also

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:56.710
in her late 70's had
come to live with us,

00:13:56.710 --> 00:13:58.720
are you counting
that's three old people

00:13:58.720 --> 00:14:00.620
who came to live with us.

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:04.140
Okay. And they came to
live with us at a time

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:10.290
when I had teenage kids who did
band and brought friends over

00:14:10.290 --> 00:14:12.310
and were starting to date.

00:14:12.310 --> 00:14:17.500
And so [foreign word], abuela
and Esa and Ola were part

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:21.320
of our life but they also did
things that drove my kids crazy

00:14:21.320 --> 00:14:25.820
like say things like this,
do you have a girlfriend?

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:28.260
Right? Oh boy.

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:33.250
And one time my son came
upstairs, that's him and Ola

00:14:33.250 --> 00:14:36.070
and he looks so upset
I said [foreign word]

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:39.670
and he says Ola came out
to say goodnight to me.

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:43.900
I said so what and he goes
she was not wearing pants.

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:47.830
Very upsetting.

00:14:47.830 --> 00:14:49.420
And so what ended
up happening is

00:14:49.420 --> 00:14:52.670
that my kids stopped
bringing home, you see my son

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:54.950
and his friends there.

00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:58.360
My kids stopped bringing
home friends and they started

00:14:58.360 --> 00:15:00.510
to leave the table quick.

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:03.670
And I felt sad about
that and I knew

00:15:03.670 --> 00:15:06.940
