00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:41.650
&gt;&gt; Why did you want
to start writing?

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:43.680
&gt;&gt; Meg Medina: You
know my family,

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:46.260
I come from a family
of story tellers.

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:49.110
They, everything about them

00:21:49.110 --> 00:21:50.800
when they were putting
away the groceries,

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:53.700
when we were driving somewhere,
when we were just sitting there

00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:57.170
like pulling the rocks out of
the bowl of beans or whatever,

00:21:57.170 --> 00:22:00.190
it always a story like,
huh I remember the time

00:22:00.190 --> 00:22:03.340
that little boy got chased
in my village by the pig.

00:22:03.340 --> 00:22:06.550
Oh I remember the time this
man ran away with so and so,

00:22:06.550 --> 00:22:09.390
on and on, it was story
and story and story.

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:11.710
And my grandmother
was the best one

00:22:11.710 --> 00:22:16.330
because she really
knew how to do drama.

00:22:16.330 --> 00:22:19.290
Like she'd get to the part
that you were like on the edge

00:22:19.290 --> 00:22:21.970
of your seat and
she'd say and you want

00:22:21.970 --> 00:22:25.810
to know what happened next
and you'd be like, yes.

00:22:25.810 --> 00:22:30.660
So she was wonderful
and so I learned early

00:22:30.660 --> 00:22:35.150
on that stories knit
us together.

00:22:35.150 --> 00:22:38.560
I learned early on that
stories sort of give you a sense

00:22:38.560 --> 00:22:41.560
of like what happened
before you.

00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:46.700
Right? And I learned
imagination through stories,

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:48.230
like just sitting
there listening

00:22:48.230 --> 00:22:51.980
to it I could imagine Cuba,
I could imagine chickens,

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:56.050
I could imagine these big
juicy mango's, like all of it

00:22:56.050 --> 00:23:01.400
and then it just
became part of how I am.

